<Layout>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>üí° Tips for Designing Prompts</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">
            5 practical rules that separate a mediocre prompt from a great one ‚Äî
            with real before/after examples
        </p>
        <div class="doc-link">
            <a
                href="https://www.promptingguide.ai/introduction/tips"
                target="_blank">üìÑ View Original Docs ‚Äî promptingguide.ai</a
            >
        </div>

        <!-- Progress -->
        <div class="progress-wrap" id="progress-wrap">
            <div class="progress-step" onclick="goTo(0)"></div>
            <div class="progress-step" onclick="goTo(1)"></div>
            <div class="progress-step" onclick="goTo(2)"></div>
            <div class="progress-step" onclick="goTo(3)"></div>
            <div class="progress-step" onclick="goTo(4)"></div>
            <div class="progress-step" onclick="goTo(5)"></div>
        </div>

        <!-- Tip nav -->
        <div class="tip-nav">
            <div class="tip-btn active" onclick="goTo(0)" id="btn-0">
                üöÄ Start Simple
            </div>
            <div class="tip-btn" onclick="goTo(1)" id="btn-1">
                üìã Use Instructions
            </div>
            <div class="tip-btn" onclick="goTo(2)" id="btn-2">
                üéØ Be Specific
            </div>
            <div class="tip-btn" onclick="goTo(3)" id="btn-3">
                ‚úÇÔ∏è Avoid Vagueness
            </div>
            <div class="tip-btn" onclick="goTo(4)" id="btn-4">
                ‚úÖ Do vs Don't
            </div>
            <div class="tip-btn" onclick="goTo(5)" id="btn-5">
                üìã Cheat Sheet
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- TIP 1: Start Simple -->
        <div class="tip-card active" id="tip-0">
            <div class="tip-header">
                <div class="tip-number">1</div>
                <div class="tip-title">üöÄ Start Simple</div>
            </div>
            <p class="tip-desc">
                Don't try to write the perfect prompt on your first try. Start
                with the simplest version, see what the AI gives you, then add
                more details step by step until you get what you want. Prompt
                engineering is an <strong style="color:#e2e8f0;"
                    >iterative process</strong
                >.
            </p>
            <div class="tip-hint">
                üß† <strong>Think of it like cooking:</strong> You don't add all the
                spices at once. You taste, adjust, taste again. Same with prompts
                ‚Äî write, test, improve, repeat.
            </div>

            <div class="rule-box">
                <h4>How to apply this:</h4>
                <ul class="rule-list">
                    <li>Start with 1 sentence ‚Äî just the instruction</li>
                    <li>If the answer is off, add context or an example</li>
                    <li>If it's too long/short, add a length instruction</li>
                    <li>
                        If you have a big task, break it into smaller subtasks
                        first
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="compare">
                <div class="compare-box before">
                    <div class="compare-label">‚ùå WRONG APPROACH</div>
                    <pre>Write a detailed, comprehensive, structured, professional summary of the following article with key takeaways, a TLDR, bullet points for each section, and a conclusion that ties it all together in an engaging way for a business audience...</pre>
                    <div class="verdict">
                        üòµ Too much at once ‚Äî easy to get confused output
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="compare-box after">
                    <div class="compare-label">‚úÖ RIGHT APPROACH</div>
                    <pre>Step 1: Summarize this article in 3 sentences.
[test it]

Step 2: Now add 3 bullet points.
[test it]

Step 3: Add a TLDR at the top.
[done!]</pre>
                    <div class="verdict">
                        ‚úÖ Build up gradually ‚Äî better control
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="nav-btns">
                <button class="nav-btn" disabled>‚Üê Previous</button>
                <button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="goTo(1)">Next ‚Üí</button
                >
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- TIP 2: Use Instructions -->
        <div class="tip-card" id="tip-1">
            <div class="tip-header">
                <div class="tip-number">2</div>
                <div class="tip-title">üìã Use Clear Instructions</div>
            </div>
            <p class="tip-desc">
                Start your prompt with a strong action verb that tells the AI
                exactly what operation to perform. Place the instruction at the <strong
                    style="color:#e2e8f0;">beginning</strong
                > of your prompt, and use a separator like <code
                    style="color:#a78bfa;">###</code
                > to split the instruction from the content.
            </p>
            <div class="tip-hint">
                üß† <strong>Common power verbs:</strong> Write, Classify, Summarize,
                Translate, Extract, List, Compare, Explain, Generate, Convert, Fix,
                Rewrite
            </div>

            <div class="compare">
                <div class="compare-box before">
                    <div class="compare-label">‚ùå NO CLEAR INSTRUCTION</div>
                    <pre>The text below is in English.
"hello!"</pre>
                    <div class="output-label">Output:</div>
                    <div class="output-text">
                        Yes, "hello!" is an English greeting... (not what you
                        wanted!)
                    </div>
                    <div class="verdict">‚ùå AI guessed what to do wrong</div>
                </div>
                <div class="compare-box after">
                    <div class="compare-label">
                        ‚úÖ CLEAR INSTRUCTION + SEPARATOR
                    </div>
                    <pre>### Instruction ###
Translate the text below to Spanish:

Text: "hello!"</pre>
                    <div class="output-label">Output:</div>
                    <div class="output-text">
                        ¬°Hola!
                    </div>
                    <div class="verdict">‚úÖ AI knew exactly what to do</div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="nav-btns">
                <button class="nav-btn" onclick="goTo(0)">‚Üê Previous</button>
                <button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="goTo(2)">Next ‚Üí</button
                >
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- TIP 3: Be Specific -->
        <div class="tip-card" id="tip-2">
            <div class="tip-header">
                <div class="tip-number">3</div>
                <div class="tip-title">üéØ Be Specific</div>
            </div>
            <p class="tip-desc">
                The more descriptive and detailed your prompt, the better the
                result. Describe the exact format you want, who the audience is,
                what style to use, and what to include or exclude. <strong
                    style="color:#e2e8f0;"
                    >Vague prompts = vague answers.</strong
                >
            </p>
            <div class="tip-hint">
                üß† <strong
                    >Imagine describing your task to a very literal assistant</strong
                > who does exactly what you say, nothing more, nothing less. Be precise
                enough that there's only ONE way to interpret your request.
            </div>

            <div class="compare">
                <div class="compare-box before">
                    <div class="compare-label">‚ùå TOO VAGUE</div>
                    <pre>Extract places from this text.

"Henrique Veiga-Fernandes works at the Champalimaud Centre in Lisbon."</pre>
                    <div class="output-label">Output:</div>
                    <div class="output-text">
                        Champalimaud Centre, Lisbon (format unknown, messy)
                    </div>
                    <div class="verdict">
                        ‚ùå No format specified ‚Äî unpredictable output
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="compare-box after">
                    <div class="compare-label">‚úÖ SPECIFIC WITH FORMAT</div>
                    <pre>Extract the name of places in the text below.

Desired format:
Place: &lt;comma_separated_list&gt;

Text: "Henrique Veiga-Fernandes works at the Champalimaud Centre in Lisbon."</pre>
                    <div class="output-label">Output:</div>
                    <div class="output-text">
                        Place: Champalimaud Centre, Lisbon
                    </div>
                    <div class="verdict">
                        ‚úÖ Clean, structured, predictable output
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="nav-btns">
                <button class="nav-btn" onclick="goTo(1)">‚Üê Previous</button>
                <button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="goTo(3)">Next ‚Üí</button
                >
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- TIP 4: Avoid Impreciseness -->
        <div class="tip-card" id="tip-3">
            <div class="tip-header">
                <div class="tip-number">4</div>
                <div class="tip-title">‚úÇÔ∏è Avoid Vagueness</div>
            </div>
            <p class="tip-desc">
                There's a difference between being <em>detailed</em> and being <em
                    >vague</em
                >. Saying "keep it short" is vague. Saying "use exactly 2
                sentences" is specific. Always replace fuzzy words with concrete
                ones ‚Äî numbers, names, formats, examples.
            </p>
            <div class="tip-hint">
                üß† <strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> If 10 different people read your
                prompt, would they all imagine the same output? If not ‚Äî it's too
                vague. Make it concrete enough that everyone pictures the same thing.
            </div>

            <div class="compare">
                <div class="compare-box before">
                    <div class="compare-label">‚ùå VAGUE WORDS</div>
                    <pre>Explain prompt engineering. Keep it short, only a few sentences, and don't be too descriptive.</pre>
                    <div class="verdict">
                        ‚ùå "A few"? "Not too descriptive"? These mean different
                        things to different people
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="compare-box after">
                    <div class="compare-label">‚úÖ CONCRETE AND CLEAR</div>
                    <pre>Use 2-3 sentences to explain prompt engineering to a high school student.</pre>
                    <div class="verdict">
                        ‚úÖ Exact count + target audience = no ambiguity
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="rule-box">
                <h4>Replace vague words with concrete ones:</h4>
                <ul class="rule-list">
                    <li>"Short" ‚Üí "2-3 sentences" or "under 50 words"</li>
                    <li>
                        "Simple" ‚Üí "for a 10-year-old" or "no technical terms"
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        "Professional" ‚Üí "formal tone, no contractions, business
                        language"
                    </li>
                    <li>"A few examples" ‚Üí "give exactly 3 examples"</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="nav-btns">
                <button class="nav-btn" onclick="goTo(2)">‚Üê Previous</button>
                <button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="goTo(4)">Next ‚Üí</button
                >
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- TIP 5: Do vs Don't -->
        <div class="tip-card" id="tip-4">
            <div class="tip-header">
                <div class="tip-number">5</div>
                <div class="tip-title">
                    ‚úÖ Say What TO Do, Not What NOT To Do
                </div>
            </div>
            <p class="tip-desc">
                When you tell the AI "DON'T do X", it often still does X ‚Äî
                because the instruction puts X in focus. Instead, tell the AI
                what it <strong style="color:#e2e8f0;">should</strong> do. Positive
                instructions work better than negative ones.
            </p>
            <div class="tip-hint">
                üß† <strong>The pink elephant problem:</strong> If I say "don't think
                of a pink elephant" ‚Äî you just did. Same with AI. "Don't ask for preferences"
                makes the AI think about asking for preferences. Say "recommend from
                trending movies" instead.
            </div>

            <div class="compare">
                <div class="compare-box before">
                    <div class="compare-label">‚ùå NEGATIVE INSTRUCTIONS</div>
                    <pre>The following is a movie recommender agent.

DO NOT ASK FOR INTERESTS.
DO NOT ASK FOR PERSONAL INFORMATION.

Customer: Recommend me a movie.
Agent:</pre>
                    <div class="output-label">Output (AI still does it!):</div>
                    <div class="output-text">
                        "Sure! What kind of movies do you like? Do you prefer
                        action, comedy...?"
                    </div>
                    <div class="verdict">
                        ‚ùå AI ignored "DO NOT" and asked anyway
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="compare-box after">
                    <div class="compare-label">‚úÖ POSITIVE INSTRUCTIONS</div>
                    <pre>You are a movie recommender. Recommend from the top global trending movies. If you can't find one, say "Sorry, no movie today."

Customer: Recommend me a movie.
Agent:</pre>
                    <div class="output-label">Output:</div>
                    <div class="output-text">
                        "Here are the top trending movies right now: [list]. I
                        hope you find one you like!"
                    </div>
                    <div class="verdict">
                        ‚úÖ AI followed the positive direction perfectly
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="nav-btns">
                <button class="nav-btn" onclick="goTo(3)">‚Üê Previous</button>
                <button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="goTo(5)"
                    >See Cheat Sheet ‚Üí</button
                >
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- CHEAT SHEET -->
        <div class="cheatsheet" id="tip-5">
            <h2
                style="font-size:1.2rem; color:#fff; margin-bottom:1rem; text-align:center;"
            >
                üìã Full Cheat Sheet ‚Äî 5 Tips at a Glance
            </h2>
            <div class="cheat-grid">
                <div class="cheat-card">
                    <h4>üöÄ 1. Start Simple</h4>
                    <p>
                        Start with the simplest version of your prompt. Test it,
                        then add details one at a time. Don't try to be perfect
                        on the first try.
                    </p>
                    <div class="example">Write ‚Üí test ‚Üí improve ‚Üí repeat</div>
                </div>
                <div class="cheat-card">
                    <h4>üìã 2. Use Clear Instructions</h4>
                    <p>
                        Start with a strong verb. Use ### to separate
                        instruction from content. Put the instruction first.
                    </p>
                    <div class="example">
                        ### Instruction ### Translate to Spanish: Text: "hello!"
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="cheat-card">
                    <h4>üéØ 3. Be Specific</h4>
                    <p>
                        Describe the exact format, audience, and style you want.
                        Include an output format example when possible.
                    </p>
                    <div class="example">
                        Desired format: Place: &lt;comma_separated_list&gt;
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="cheat-card">
                    <h4>‚úÇÔ∏è 4. Avoid Vagueness</h4>
                    <p>
                        Replace fuzzy words with concrete ones. Numbers beat
                        adjectives every time.
                    </p>
                    <div class="example">
                        "short" ‚Üí "2-3 sentences" "simple" ‚Üí "for a 10-year-old"
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="cheat-card" style="grid-column: span 2;">
                    <h4>‚úÖ 5. Say What TO Do (Not What NOT To Do)</h4>
                    <p>
                        Positive instructions are more effective. Instead of
                        "DON'T ask for preferences", say "Recommend from
                        trending movies only."
                    </p>
                    <div class="example">
                        ‚ùå DO NOT ask for interests ‚úÖ Recommend from the top 10
                        global trending movies
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-banner" style="margin-top:1.2rem;">
                <span style="font-size:1.4rem; flex-shrink:0;">üí°</span>
                <p>
                    <strong>The Golden Rule:</strong> A great prompt is like a great
                    job description ‚Äî specific enough that there's only one way to
                    interpret it, but not so long that it becomes overwhelming. Start
                    simple, be specific, use positive instructions.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="nav-btns">
                <button class="nav-btn" onclick="goTo(4)">‚Üê Previous</button>
                <button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="goTo(0)"
                    >‚Ü© Start Over</button
                >
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</Layout>
<style>
    .container {
        padding: 2rem;
